sec.p:
Modal amplitude coherence (MAC), an index indicating the similarity between measured response and the identified model's response, can be used to extract physical modes from vibration signals. When the MAC of mode tends to 1, the corresponding mode is considered to be a physical mode. However, it is found that MAC alone can barely identify the physical and noise mode, because some MAC value of the noise mode is also close to 1. To exclude the influence of noise modes, a de-noising technique and FFT are used together with ERA in this paper to identify modal parameters. The modal parameter identification is conducted based on the following procedure:


Firstly, the measured signal is de-noised using Daubechies-8 type wavelet filter;

Then, ERA is applied to the de-noised signal to extract model parameters, including natural frequency, damping ratio and mode shape. Note that adopted modal parameters must be stable for models of increasing orders. Modes that exist in most of these models with consistent frequency, damping ratio and mode shape are considered stable and are likely to be physical;

The natural frequency extracted from ERA method (step 2) is compared with the result of FFT. If it exists in both ERA and FFT results, the frequency and corresponding mode shape are reserved. If the frequency exists in the ERA results but not in the FFT results, it is considered as noise mode and discarded.

Steps (1)–(3) are performed repetitively with multiple datasets. Only the mode with stable parameters (including frequency and mode shape) in different datasets is taken as the physical mode.
